04029nam a22006615i 9780292763197DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20221994txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927631977 a10.7560/7045412doi  a(DE-B1597)586805  a(OCoLC)1312727233  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aBIO0020002bisacsh1 aAllison, Mary Bruins, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDoctor Mary in Arabia :bMemoirs /cMary Bruins Allison; ed. by Sandra J. Shaw. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2022] 4c©1994  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUntil fairly recently, Arab women rarely received professional health care, since few women doctors had ever practiced in Arabia and their culture forbade them from consulting male doctors. Not surprisingly, Dr. Mary Bruins Allison faced an overwhelming demand when she arrived in Kuwait in 1934 as a medical missionary of the Reformed Church of America. Over the next forty years, "Dr. Mary" treated thousands of women and children, faithfully performing the duties that seemed required of her as a Christian—to heal the sick and seek converts. These memoirs record a fascinating life. Dr. Allison briefly describes her upbringing and her professional training at Women's Medical College of Pennsylvania. She then focuses on her experiences in Kuwait, where women of all classes, including royalty, flocked to her care. In addition to describing many of her cases, Dr. Allison paints a richly detailed picture of life in Kuwait both before and after the discovery of oil transformed the country. Her recollections include invaluable details of women's lives in the Middle East during the early and mid-twentieth century. They add a valuable chapter to the story of modern medicine, to the largely unsuccessful efforts of the Christian church to win converts in the Middle East, and to the opportunities and limitations that faced American women of the period. Dr. Allison also worked briefly in Bahrain, Qatar, Oman, and India, and she includes material on each country. The introduction situates her experiences in the context of Middle Eastern and medical developments of the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Cultural Heritage.2bisacsh1 aSaunders, John Clarke, John Clarke, M.D.1 aSaunders, Lucie Wood, Lucie Wood, Ph.D.1 aShaw, Sandra J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311074535140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70454140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292763197423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292763197/original  a978-3-11-074535-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK